Special Functions for Confusion Matrix, Precision-Recall Curve¶

The reason using AUPRC instead of AUC

We know that ROC curve is TPR (sensitivity, or true positive rate) vs FPR (false positive rate), while precision-recall curve is precision (positive predicted value) vs recall, i.e. sensitivity, TPR.

We can see that ROC cares both true positive and true negative. And precision-recall curve is only concerned about TP over both condition positive and predicted condition positive. Thus,

In [22]:
# define function to perform train, test, and get model performance
def train_test_model_AUPRC(clf, X_train, y_train, X_test, y_test):
    start = time.clock()
    # Fit a model by providing X and y from training set
    clf.fit(X_train, y_train)
    print('Model fitting time is %.2fs'%(time.clock()-start))
    
    # Make prediction on the training data
    y_train_pred = clf.predict(X_train)
    p_train_pred = clf.predict_proba(X_train)[:,1]

    # Make predictions on test data
    y_test_pred = clf.predict(X_test)
    p_test_pred = clf.predict_proba(X_test)[:,1]

    # print model results
    get_performance_metrics_AUPRC(y_train, p_train_pred, y_test, p_test_pred)
    plot_AUPRC_CM(y_train, p_train_pred, y_test, y_test_pred, p_test_pred)
#     plot_AUPR_curve(y_train, p_train_pred, y_test, p_test_pred)


# plot AUPRC and CM(confusion matrix)
def plot_AUPRC_CM(y_train, p_train_pred, y_test, y_test_pred, p_test_pred):
    %matplotlib inline
    auprc_train = average_precision_score(y_train, p_train_pred)
    precision_train, recall_train, _ = precision_recall_curve(y_train, p_train_pred)

    auprc_test = average_precision_score(y_test, p_test_pred)
    precision_test, recall_test, _ = precision_recall_curve(y_test, p_test_pred)
        
    fig, (ax1, ax2) = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(13,5))
    
    lw = 2
    ax1.plot(recall_train, precision_train, color='green',
             lw=lw, label='PRC Train (AUPRC = %0.4f)' % auprc_train)
    ax1.plot(recall_test, precision_test, color='darkorange',
             lw=lw, label='PRC Test (AUPRC = %0.4f)' % auprc_test)
    ax1.plot([1, 0], [0, 1], color='navy', lw=lw, linestyle='--') 
    ax1.set_xlim([0.0, 1.0])
    ax1.set_ylim([0.0, 1.05])
    ax1.set_xlabel('Recall')
    ax1.set_ylabel('Precision')
    ax1.set_title('Precision recall curve example', fontsize=14)
    ax1.legend(loc="lower right")
        
    cm = confusion_matrix(y_test, y_test_pred)
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=True, cmap='coolwarm_r')
    ax2.set_title("Confusion Matrix", fontsize=14)
    ax2.set_xticklabels(['pred 0', 'pred 1'], fontsize=10, rotation=90)
    ax2.set_yticklabels(['true 0', 'true 1'], fontsize=10, rotation=360)
    
    plt.show()

# Helper method to print metric scores    
def get_performance_metrics_AUPRC(y_train, y_train_pred, y_test, y_test_pred, threshold=0.5):
    metric_names = ['AUPRC', 'Precision','Recall','f1-score', 'AUC','Accuracy',]
    metric_values_train = [average_precision_score(y_train, y_train_pred),
                    precision_score(y_train, y_train_pred>threshold),
                    recall_score(y_train, y_train_pred>threshold),
                    f1_score(y_train, y_train_pred>threshold),
                    roc_auc_score(y_train, y_train_pred),
                    accuracy_score(y_train, y_train_pred>threshold)
                    ]
    metric_values_test = [average_precision_score(y_test, y_test_pred),
                    precision_score(y_test, y_test_pred>threshold),
                    recall_score(y_test, y_test_pred>threshold),
                    f1_score(y_test, y_test_pred>threshold),
                    roc_auc_score(y_test, y_test_pred),
                    accuracy_score(y_test, y_test_pred>threshold),
                    ]
    all_metrics = pd.DataFrame({'metrics':metric_names,
                                'train':metric_values_train,
                                'test':metric_values_test},columns=['metrics','train','test']).set_index('metrics')

    print(all_metrics)

Make GridSearch Resampling Pipeline¶

If we want to implement cross validation, remember to oversample or undersample your training data during cross-validation, not before!

In [29]:
# rus: random under sampler;  _rs: resampling

rs_seed = 901
# rs_method = RandomUnderSampler()
# rs_method = NearMiss(n_jobs=7)
rs_method = SMOTE(n_jobs=7, random_state=rs_seed)
# rs_method = SMOTEENN(n_jobs=7)
In [30]:
lr_rs_clf = LogisticRegression()

# logistic regression pipeline: rsClf (resample + clf(classifier) )
lr_rsClf_pipeline = Pipeline([('rs_method', rs_method), ('lr_rs_clf', lr_rs_clf)])

rsClf_pipeline_param_grid = {'lr_rs_clf__C': [5, 10, 20, 30, 40], 
                             'lr_rs_clf__penalty': ['l2']                            }
